# Enterprise Accessibility & Contrast Standard (Frozen)

Applies across Catalyst One, Catalyst Connect, and future platforms.

## Objective

The interface must remain readable under every interaction state.

Whenever an item is hovered, focused, selected, active, pressed, or disabled, there must always be sufficient visual contrast between:

- Background
- Text
- Icons
- Borders
- Status badges

No interaction may reduce readability.

## Forbidden patterns

- Light text on bright / light backgrounds
- Dark text on dark backgrounds
- Hover or focus that changes background without also setting a matching foreground
- Using bright success / warning / info colors as generic hover fills without a paired foreground token
- Disabled states that rely only on low opacity of already-low-contrast text

## Required patterns

1. Interactive surfaces must pair background + foreground tokens together (e.g. `bg-accent` with `text-accent-foreground`).
2. Prefer semantic tokens (`accent`, `muted`, `primary`, `destructive`) over one-off hex pairs for interaction states.
3. Selection / active feedback must stay readable — visibility alone is not enough.
4. Status badges keep high-contrast label colors on their own surfaces in every state.
5. Focus rings remain visible (`ring` / `ring-offset`) without washing out label text.
6. Disabled: keep structure visible; use muted foreground + moderate opacity, not washed-out light-on-light.

## Token ownership

- `--accent` / `--accent-foreground` = interactive highlight (hover, focus, selected menu items)
- `--success` / `--warning` / `--info` = status semantics only — not generic hover fills
- `--primary` / `--primary-foreground` = primary actions

## When changing UI

Review hover, focus, selected, active, pressed, and disabled before shipping. Prefer fixing primitives in `src/components/ui/` so all workspaces inherit contrast.
